\\subsection{central processor unit (CPU)}
Also called processor. The active part of the computer, which contains the datapath and control and which adds numbers, tests numbers, signals I/O devices to activate, and so on.

\\subsection{datapath}
The component of the processor that performs arithmetic operations.

gyroscope, Wi-Fi network, and Bluetooth network. The datapath, control, and memory are a tiny portion of the components.

The small rectangles in Figure~\\ref{fig:1.8} contain the devices that drive our advancing technology, called \\textbf{integrated circuits} and nicknamed \\textbf{chips}. The A12 package seen in the middle of in Figure~\\ref{fig:1.8} contains two large and four little ARM processors that operate with a clock rate of 2.5 GHz. The \\textit{processor} is the active part of the computer, following the instructions of a program to the letter. It adds numbers, tests numbers, signals I/O devices to activate, and so on. Occasionally, people call the processor the \\textbf{CPU}, for the more bureaucratic-sounding \\textbf{central processor unit}.

Descending even lower into the hardware, Figure~\\ref{fig:1.9} reveals details of a microprocessor. The processor logically comprises two main components: datapath and control, the respective brawn and brain of the processor. The \\textbf{datapath} performs the arithmetic operations, and \\textbf{control} tells the datapath,

