\\section{Allocating Space for New Data on the Heap}

In addition to automatic variables that are local to procedures, C programmers need space in memory for static variables and for dynamic data structures. Figure 2.13 shows the RISC-V convention for allocation of memory when running the Linux operating system. The stack starts in the high end of the user addresses space (see Chapter 5) and grows down. The first part of the low end of memory is reserved, followed by the home of the RISC-V machine code, traditionally called the \\textbf{text segment}. Above the code is the \\textit{static data segment}, which is the place for constants and other static variables. Although arrays tend to be a fixed length and thus are a good match to the static data segment, data structures like linked lists tend to grow and shrink during their lifetimes. The segment for such data structures is traditionally called the \\textit{heap}, and it is placed next in memory. Note that this allocation allows the stack and heap to grow toward each other, thereby allowing the efficient use of memory as the two segments wax and wane.

\\textbf{text segment} The segment of a UNIX object file that contains the machine language code for routines in the source file.

\\section{2.9 Communicating with People}
\\subsection*{Elaboration:} Reflecting the international nature of the web, most web pages today use Unicode instead of ASCII. Hence, Unicode may be even more popular than ASCII today.

\\textbf{Check Yourself}

\\begin{enumerate}
    \\item A string in C takes about half the memory as the same string in Java.
    \\item Strings are just an informal name for single-dimension arrays of characters in C and Java.
    \\item Strings in C and Java use null (0) to mark the end of a string.
    \\item Operations on strings, like length, are faster in C than in Java.
\\end{enumerate}

\\textbf{II.} Which type of variable that can contain $1,000,000,000_{\\text{ten}}$ takes the most memory space?

\\begin{enumerate}
    \\item \\texttt{int} in C
    \\item \\texttt{string} in C
    \\item \\texttt{string} in Java
\\end{enumerate}

\\textbf{The BIG Picture}

Newcomers to computing are surprised that the type of the data is not encoded inside the data but instead in the \\textit{program} that operates on that data.

As an analogy, what does the word ``won'' mean? You can't answer that question without knowing the context, specifically the language it is supposed to be in. Here are four alternatives:

\\begin{enumerate}
    \\item In English, it is the verb that is the past tense of win.
    \\item In Korean, it is a noun that is the monetary unit of South Korea.
    \\item In Polish, it is an adjective that means nice-smelling.
    \\item In Russian, it is an adjective that means stinks.
\\end{enumerate}

A binary number can also represent several types of data. For example, the 32-bit pattern $01100010\\ 01100001\\ 01010000\\ 00000000$ could represent:

\\begin{enumerate}
    \\item $1,650,544,640$ if the program treats it as an unsigned integer.
    \\item $+1,650,544,640$ if the program treats it as a signed integer.
    \\item ``baP'' if the program treats it as a null-terminated ASCII string.
    \\item The color dark blue if the program treats the bit pattern as a mixture of the four base colors cyan, magenta, yellow, and black of the Pantone color-matching system.
\\end{enumerate}

\\subsection{RISC-V Addressing for Wide Immediates and Addresses}
\\label{sec:riscv-addressing}

\\begin{figure}[htbp]
\\centering
\\includegraphics[width=\\textwidth]{_page_0_Figure_2.jpeg}
\\caption{Illustration of four RISC-V addressing modes. The operands are shaded in color. The operand of mode 3 is in memory, whereas the operand for mode 2 is a register. Note that versions of load and store access bytes, halfwords, words. For mode 1, the operand is part of the instruction itself. Mode 4 addresses instructions in memory, with mode 4 adding a long address to the PC. Note that a single operation can use more than one addressing mode. Add, for example, uses both immediate (\\texttt{addi}) and register (\\texttt{add}) addressing.}
\\label{fig:riscv-addressing-modes}
\\end{figure}

\\subsubsection{RISC-V Addressing Mode Summary}
Multiple forms of addressing are generically called \\textbf{addressing modes}. Figure \\ref{fig:riscv-addressing-modes} shows how operands are identified for each addressing mode. The addressing modes of the RISC-V instructions are the following:

\\begin{enumerate}
    \\item \\textit{Immediate addressing}, where the operand is a constant within the instruction itself.
    \\item \\textit{Register addressing}, where the operand is a register.
    \\item \\textit{Base} or \\textit{displacement addressing}, where the operand is at the memory location whose address is the sum of a register and a constant in the instruction.
    \\item \\textit{PC-relative addressing}, where the branch address is the sum of the PC and a constant in the instruction.
\\end{enumerate}

\\textbf{addressing mode} One of several addressing regimes delimited by their varied use of operands and/or addresses.

