with the \\texttt{and} instruction are delayed one cycle. Like an air bubble in a water pipe, a stall bubble delays everything behind it and proceeds down the instruction pipe one stage each clock cycle until it exits at the end. In this example, the hazard forces the \\texttt{and} and \\texttt{or} instructions to repeat in clock cycle 4 what they did in clock cycle 3: \\texttt{and} reads registers and decodes, and \\texttt{or} is refetched from instruction memory. Such repeated work is what a stall looks like, but its effect is to stretch the time of the \\texttt{and} and \\texttt{or} instructions and delay the fetch of the \\texttt{add} instruction.

Figure 4.62 highlights the pipeline connections for both the hazard detection unit and the forwarding unit. As before, the forwarding unit controls the ALU multiplexors to replace the value from a general-purpose register with the value from the proper pipeline register. The hazard detection unit controls the writing of the PC and IF/ID registers plus the multiplexor that chooses between the real control values and all 0s. The hazard detection unit stalls and deasserts the control fields if the load-use hazard test above is true. If you would like to see more details, \\textbf{Section 4.14} gives an example illustrated using single-clock pipeline diagrams of RISC-V code with hazards that cause stalling.

