\\begin{enumerate}
    \\item The \\textit{core sequencer} executes \\textit{VLIW} instructions from the core's on-chip, software-managed instruction memory (Imem), executes scalar operations using a 4K 32-bit scalar data memory (Smem) and 32 32-bit scalar registers (Sregs), and forwards vector instructions to the \\textit{vector processing unit} (VPU). The 322-bit VLIW instruction can launch eight operations: two scalar ALUs, two vector ALUs, vector load and store, and a pair of slots that queue data to and from the matrix multiply and transpose units.

    \\item The VPU performs vector operations using a large on-chip vector memory (Vmem) with 32K 128 $\\times$ 32-bit elements (16 MiB), and 32 2D vector registers (Vregs) that each contain 128 $\\times$ 8 32-bit elements (4 KiB). The VPU collects and distributes data to Vmem via data-level (2D matrix and vector functional units) and instruction-level parallelism (8 operations per instruction).

    \\item The MXU produces 32-bit FP products from 16-bit FP inputs that accumulate in 32 bits. All other computations are in 32-bit FP except for results going directly to an MXU input, which are converted to 16-bit FP. TPUv3 has two MXUs per TensorCore.

    \\item The Transpose Reduction Permute Unit does 128$\\times$128 matrix transposes, reductions, and permutations of the VPU lanes.
\\end{enumerate}

