Which of the following define exactly the same value?
\\begin{enumerate}
    \\item $8'b10000000$
    \\item $8'hF0$
    \\item $8'd240$
    \\item $\\{ \\{4\\{1'b1\\} \\}, \\{4\\{1'b0\\} \\} \\}$
    \\item $\\{4'b1, 4'b0\\}$
\\end{enumerate}

\\subsection{Structure of a Verilog Program}
A Verilog program is structured as a set of modules, which may represent anything from a collection of logic gates to a complete system. Modules are similar to classes in C++, although not nearly as powerful. A module specifies its input and output ports, which describe the incoming and outgoing connections of a module. A module may also declare additional variables. The body of a module consists of:
\\begin{itemize}
    \\item \\texttt{initial} constructs, which can initialize \\texttt{reg} variables
    \\item Continuous assignments, which define only combinational logic
    \\item \\texttt{always} constructs, which can define either sequential or combinational logic
    \\item Instances of other modules, which are used to implement the module being defined
\\end{itemize}

\\subsection{Representing Complex Combinational Logic in Verilog}
A continuous assignment, which is indicated with the keyword \\texttt{assign}, acts like a combinational logic function: the output is continuously assigned the value, and a change in the input values is reflected immediately in the output value. Wires may only be assigned values with continuous assignments. Using continuous assignments, we can define a module that implements a half-adder, as Figure~A.4.1 shows.

Assign statements are one sure way to write Verilog that generates combinational logic. For more complex structures, however, assign statements may be awkward or tedious to use. It is also possible to use the \\texttt{always} block of a module to describe a combinational logic element, although care must be taken. Using an \\texttt{always} block allows the inclusion of Verilog control constructs, such as \\texttt{if-then-else}, \\texttt{case} statements, \\texttt{for} statements, and \\texttt{repeat} statements, to be used. These statements are similar to those in C with small changes.

An \\texttt{always} block specifies an optional list of signals on which the block is sensitive (in a list starting with @). The \\texttt{always} block is re-evaluated if any of the

\\begin{verbatim}
module half_adder (A,B,Sum,Carry);
    input A,B; //two 1-bit inputs
    output Sum, Carry; //two 1-bit outputs
    assign Sum = A ^ B; //sum is A xor B
    assign Carry = A & B; //Carry is A and B
endmodule
\\end{verbatim}

\\textbf{FIGURE A.4.1} A Verilog module that defines a half-adder using continuous assignments.

