\\subsection{Defining the RISC-V ALU in Verilog}
Figure A.5.15 shows how a combinational RISC-V ALU might be specified in Verilog; such a specification would probably be compiled using a standard parts library that provided an adder, which could be instantiated. For completeness, we show the ALU control for RISC-V in Figure A.5.16, which is used in Chapter 4, where we build a Verilog version of the RISC-V datapath.

\\begin{figure}[h]
\\centering
\\includegraphics[width=0.5\\textwidth]{_page_0_Picture_2.jpeg}
\\caption{The symbol commonly used to represent an ALU, as shown in Figure A.5.12. This symbol is also used to represent an adder, so it is normally labeled either with ALU or Adder.}
\\label{fig:alu_symbol}
\\end{figure}

\\begin{figure}[h]
\\centering
\\begin{verbatim}
module RISCVALU (ALUctl, A, B, ALUOut, Zero);
  input [3:0] ALUctl;
  input [31:0] A,B;
  output reg [31:0] ALUOut;
  output Zero;
  assign Zero = (ALUOut==0); //Zero is true if ALUOut is 0
  always @(ALUctl, A, B) begin //reevaluate if these change
    case (ALUctl)
      0: ALUOut <= A & B;
      1: ALUOut <= A | B;
      2: ALUOut <= A + B;
      6: ALUOut <= A - B;
      7: ALUOut <= A < B ? 1 : 0;
      12: ALUOut <= ~(A | B); // result is nor
      default: ALUOut <= 0;
    endcase
  end
endmodule
\\end{verbatim}
