\\subsection*{A.32} [20] $<$\\S A.6$>$ Perhaps the most likely case of adding many numbers at once in a computer would be when trying to multiply more quickly by using many adders to add many numbers in a single clock cycle. Compared to the multiply algorithm in Chapter 3, a carry save scheme with many adders could multiply more than 10 times faster. This exercise estimates the cost and speed of a combinational multiplier to multiply two positive 16-bit numbers. Assume that you have 16 intermediate terms $M_{15}, M_{14}, \\ldots, M_{0}$, called \\emph{partial products}, that contain the multiplicand ANDed with multiplier bits $m_{15}, m_{14}, \\ldots, m_{0}$. The idea is to use carry save adders to reduce the $n$ operands into $2n/3$ in parallel groups of three, and do this repeatedly until you get two large numbers to add together with a traditional adder.

