\\section{D.5 The IBM 360/370 Architecture for Mainframe Computers}

\\subsection{Introduction}

The term ``computer architecture'' was coined by IBM in 1964 for use with the IBM 360. Amdahl, Blaauw, and Brooks [1964] used the term to refer to the programmer-visible portion of the instruction set. They believed that a family of machines of the same architecture should be able to run the same software. Although this idea may seem obvious to us today, it was quite novel at the time. IBM, even though it was the leading company in the industry, had five different architectures before the 360. Thus, the notion of a company standardizing on a single architecture was a radical one. The 360 designers hoped that six different divisions of IBM could be brought together by defining a common \\emph{architecture}. Their definition of \\emph{architecture} was

\\ldots the structure of a computer that a machine language programmer must understand to write a correct (timing independent) program for that machine.

The term \\emph{machine language programmer} meant that compatibility would hold, even in assembly language, while \\emph{timing independent} allowed different implementations.

The IBM 360 was introduced in 1964 with six models and a 25:1 performance ratio. Amdahl, Blaauw, and Brooks [1964] discussed the architecture of the IBM 360 and the concept of permitting multiple object-code-compatible implementations. The notion of an instruction set architecture as we understand it today was the most important aspect of the 360. The \\emph{architecture} also introduced several important innovations, now in wide use:

\\begin{enumerate}
    \\item 32-bit architecture
    \\item Byte-addressable memory with 8-bit bytes
    \\item 8-, 16-, 32-, and 64-bit data sizes
    \\item 32-bit single-precision and 64-bit double-precision floating-point data
\\end{enumerate}

In 1971, IBM shipped the first System/370 (models 155 and 165), which included a number of significant extensions of the 360, as discussed by Case and Padegs [1978], who also discussed the early history of System/360. The most important addition was virtual memory, though virtual memory 370s did not ship until 1972, when a virtual memory operating system was ready. By 1978, the high-end 370 was several hundred times faster than the low-end 360s shipped 10 years earlier. In 1984, the 24-bit addressing model built into the IBM 360 needed to be abandoned, and the 370-XA (eXtended Architecture) was introduced. While old 24-bit programs could be supported without change, several instructions could not function in the same
